Author::::Quonishant
DateTime::::2016-03-07T05:34:02Z
Australia’s cooked food industry has an insatiable appetite for palm oil. Go to any supermarket, for instance, and read the label of any cooked product such as from an in or ex situ bakery and you’ll find that it contains palm oil, either by way of direct designation or by dint of having been included under the heading ‘vegetable oil’. And remember, if the label lists several types of oil, the first-mentioned is always the predominant one. So that if the label says ‘palm oil, canola oil’, the product may contain 99% palm oil, 1% canola oil.Take-away food outlets, from the most prominent ones to other places that produce cooked foods sold either hot or cold follow such a process of cooking with palm oil.Have you ever noticed how you cannot buy a bottle of palm oil in a supermarket? A couple of times I asked a store attendant to find me a bottle – just for interest’s sake. They are simply non-existent.That’s because such oil is too cheap; and that’s also the reason why the manufacturers of cooked foods use this type of oil.And the reason why palm oil is cheap is because of cheap labour costs associated with the harvesting of palm oil by, for instance, poor Sumatran natives - in the process of which natural habitats, such as where the endangered orang-utans live, are destroyed.There’s another aspect to this saga. The medical profession will tell you that palm oil is the worst oil you can stuff into your body, because it clogs up your arteries, big time; as does coconut oil, for example, which in the artery-clogging department comes second to palm oil.You may say you don’t care. But the government does care; that’s to say, it doesn’t care if you stuff yourself with this stuff because of the mantra consumption is good for business and business is good for employment and wealth, these things being important for re-election of governments.The only drawback of course is that the sicker, the unhealthier people get, the greater the dollar-burden on the nation’s health care system; and don’t we know that’s getting more and more expensive: didn’t Scott Morrison want to increase GST by 50% predominantly for that reason?



